</span></span><span><span>history </span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(234, 236, 240);">=</span><span> </span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">[</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">.</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">.</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">.</span><span> </span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">for</span><span> r</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">,</span><span> m </span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">in</span><span> st</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">.</span><span>session_state</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">.</span><span>chat_history</span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">]</span><span>  </span><span class="token token" style="color: rgb(129, 136, 152);"># now includes current message</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">So <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">chat_history</code> already contains the current user message when history is built. ✅ That's correct — no duplication issue.</p>
